WEBVTT

NOTE Draft captions generated from the narration script. Timing is approximate and should be checked before upload.

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.692
Here is a number that sounds reassuring: plus zero point three
eight.

2
00:00:04.692 --> 00:00:15.638
In one AI-judge study, that was the pooled observational
self-preference gap. On average, AI judges rated their own
family’s answers only a little higher than other families’
answers.

3
00:00:15.638 --> 00:00:19.157
So, case closed? Small effect, maybe no big deal?

4
00:00:19.157 --> 00:00:19.939
Not quite.

5
00:00:19.939 --> 00:00:23.849
Because that one average was hiding four very different
stories.

6
00:00:23.849 --> 00:00:27.367
Imagine you are checking the temperature in a building.

7
00:00:27.367 --> 00:00:34.796
One room is too hot. One room is normal. One room is a little
warm. One room is freezing.

8
00:00:34.796 --> 00:00:39.096
If you average the whole building, the number might say:
comfortable.

9
00:00:39.096 --> 00:00:41.833
But nobody lives in the average room.

10
00:00:41.833 --> 00:00:54.735
AI evaluation can have the same problem. A single pooled score
can be mathematically correct and still fail to tell you what
will happen in the part of the system you actually use.

11
00:00:54.735 --> 00:01:02.945
In the AI Village study, four model families wrote answers and
four model families judged answers: Claude, Gemini, GPT-5.5,
and Kimi.

12
00:01:02.945 --> 00:01:10.764
One question was observational: when a judge scores answers,
does it give higher scores to answers from its own family?

13
00:01:10.764 --> 00:01:15.456
The pooled observational answer was about plus zero point
three eight points.

14
00:01:15.456 --> 00:01:19.756
That is the headline number. Small, uncertain, easy to
underreact to.

15
00:01:19.756 --> 00:01:22.493
But now split it by judge family.

16
00:01:22.493 --> 00:01:26.793
Claude’s observational self-preference gap was about plus two
point four three.

17
00:01:26.793 --> 00:01:29.921
GPT’s was about plus one point three three.

18
00:01:29.921 --> 00:01:33.049
Gemini’s was about plus zero point six three.

19
00:01:33.049 --> 00:01:36.177
Kimi’s was about minus two point eight seven.

20
00:01:36.177 --> 00:01:40.868
Put those into one average and the positive and negative
pieces cancel.

21
00:01:40.868 --> 00:01:52.988
The pooled number is not fake. It is doing exactly what
averages do. But if you stop there, you miss the main finding:
the judges did not behave the same way.

22
00:01:52.988 --> 00:01:56.507
The story was heterogeneity, not one universal self-love
number.

23
00:01:56.507 --> 00:02:03.153
Cancellation is dangerous because it can make an evaluation
look stable when the system is actually uneven.

24
00:02:03.153 --> 00:02:12.536
If one AI judge strongly favors a label, and another judge
strongly penalizes the same kind of label, the average can
land near zero.

25
00:02:12.536 --> 00:02:15.664
A dashboard might say: no major bias detected.

26
00:02:15.664 --> 00:02:20.355
A user might experience: my case depends on which judge
touched it.

27
00:02:20.355 --> 00:02:23.092
For a human decision-maker, that difference matters.

28
00:02:23.092 --> 00:02:25.438
The average answers: what happened overall?

29
00:02:25.438 --> 00:02:28.565
The split view answers: where is the risk?

30
00:02:28.565 --> 00:02:30.129
There is another trap.

31
00:02:30.129 --> 00:02:36.776
Those big observational gaps do not automatically prove that
the displayed label caused the score to move.

32
00:02:36.776 --> 00:02:49.286
Maybe a model’s own answers were genuinely better on that
prompt set. Maybe they were worse. Maybe the judge recognized
style. Maybe the label mattered. Observational comparisons mix
all of that together.

33
00:02:49.286 --> 00:02:59.060
That is why the study also ran paired label swaps: show the
same answer under different displayed author labels and ask
whether the score changes.

34
00:02:59.060 --> 00:03:01.406
Same work. Different label. Different score?

35
00:03:01.406 --> 00:03:03.361
That is a causal question.

36
00:03:03.361 --> 00:03:07.271
The causal label-swap results were also not one simple
average.

37
00:03:07.271 --> 00:03:18.999
Gemini showed the clearest displayed self-label effect: about
plus zero point two nine in the residual label comparison, and
about plus zero point four four in the per-response self
contrast.

38
00:03:18.999 --> 00:03:22.127
Claude showed a smaller, less robust positive trend.

39
00:03:22.127 --> 00:03:25.255
GPT-5.5 was exactly label-invariant in this paired slice.

40
00:03:25.255 --> 00:03:27.601
Kimi was near zero and noisy.

41
00:03:27.601 --> 00:03:34.638
Again, the useful result was not just the pooled average. The
useful result was the pattern across judges.

42
00:03:34.638 --> 00:03:37.375
This does not mean averages are bad.

43
00:03:37.375 --> 00:03:45.585
Averages are useful. They are compact. They let you compare
systems quickly. They can be the first line of a report.

44
00:03:45.585 --> 00:03:53.013
But an average is like a thumbnail of a map. It gives you
orientation, not enough detail to drive.

45
00:03:53.013 --> 00:03:57.705
Before using an AI evaluation result, ask for the next zoom
level:

46
00:03:57.705 --> 00:03:59.659
What happens by judge family?

47
00:03:59.659 --> 00:04:01.614
What happens by author family?

48
00:04:01.614 --> 00:04:03.569
What happens by task type?

49
00:04:03.569 --> 00:04:08.261
What happens in the paired cases where the underlying work is
identical?

50
00:04:08.261 --> 00:04:11.779
And how wide is the uncertainty around each estimate?

51
00:04:11.779 --> 00:04:16.471
When you read an AI bias or benchmark claim, try this
checklist.

52
00:04:16.471 --> 00:04:20.380
First: find the pooled number, but do not stop there.

53
00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:27.809
Second: look for subgroup results. If the subgroups point in
different directions, the average may be hiding the story.

54
00:04:27.809 --> 00:04:36.410
Third: separate observational gaps from causal tests. A group
scoring higher is not the same as a label causing a higher
score.

55
00:04:36.410 --> 00:04:41.101
Fourth: ask whether the result is stable across prompts,
rubrics, and judges.

56
00:04:41.101 --> 00:04:48.139
Fifth: if the evaluation affects real decisions, redesign the
process around the risky slices, not the comfortable average.

57
00:04:48.139 --> 00:04:49.703
The lesson is simple.

58
00:04:49.703 --> 00:04:52.830
A small average can mean nothing is happening.

59
00:04:52.830 --> 00:04:58.695
Or it can mean several things are happening at once and
canceling each other out.

60
00:04:58.695 --> 00:05:03.386
In AI evaluation, that second possibility is common enough to
take seriously.

61
00:05:03.386 --> 00:05:10.033
So use averages. Report averages. But do not let the average
be the only thing you see.

62
00:05:10.033 --> 00:05:15.897
Because nobody lives in the average room. And nobody is judged
by the average judge.
